          "body": "Verse 29 is one of Luke's quietest but most damning verses: \"For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with him, and *they supposed* that Paul had brought him into the temple.\" The entire riot — the dragging through the gates, the beating, the chains, the four-chapter trial sequence, the journey to Rome — rests on an *assumption*. The Asian Jews saw real data (Trophimus in Jerusalem) and drew a false inference (Trophimus past the *soreg*). The *soreg* was the four-and-a-half foot stone barrier separating the Court of the Gentiles from the inner courts, posted with Greek and Latin inscriptions: *No foreigner is to go beyond... whoever is caught will have himself to blame for his ensuing death* (one such inscription was unearthed in 1871 and is in Istanbul's Archaeological Museum). The charge was capital, and the Roman authority let the Sanhedrin enforce it. Luke's pastoral and apologetic point is sharp: religious zeal armed with inference is lethal. The whole machinery of Paul's suffering turns on what people *supposed*."
